Sanji just chuckled and kissed him on the cheek before stepping out of his embrace. “C’mon. The faster we pack up the sooner I can kiss you again.”

“Better not make a habit of using that to get me to do shit.”

“Oh, I won’t.”

He would.

And Zoro wouldn’t mind one bit. 

//end

Sanji grinned, cupping Zoro’s face and thumbing across his cheekbone. “Jeez, marimo, keep saying adorable shit like that and I’ll do anything you ask.”

Zoro blushed, averting his eyes, trying (and failing) to fix his face into a frown.

Sanji pecked him on the lips once more apologetically and started to pull away, but Zoro caught him before he could leave the circle of his arms. 

“W-wait! Come over to my place after? I want to… uh…” His confidence wained as he mumbled, “Wanna kiss you more.”

Kissing Sanji was perfection.

Apparently it was too perfect a moment to last because just as Zoro went to lean in for a second one, Sanji’s phone started beeping an alarm.

“Shit, sorry,” he cursed, reaching into his pocket to silence it. “That’s our cue. We gotta head out.”

Zoro took a deep breath, letting it out shakily as he nodded. 

It wasn’t Zoro’s first kiss, but it may as well have been because all of those other kisses paled in comparison to this one. He had never kissed someone he had feelings for and, oh god, this was on another level.

Sanji shifted beside him. “Hey, Zoro?”

“Hm?”

Sanji’s fingertips skated along Zoro’s jaw, gently turning his face towards him. His eyes flicked down to Zoro’s parted lips and then back up again. “Can I kiss you?”

He knew if he tried to look at him he’d lose his nerve.

“This is really nice. I’m glad we decided to do this. Being together, I mean. It’s… I really couldn’t see myself doing this with anyone else, but with you it feels… dunno… just feels right,” Zoro confessed quietly.

After a moment of content silence, Zoro spoke up again, “Sanji?”

He could hear the other man’s sharp intake of breath and felt his grip tighten ever so slightly, viscerally affected by the sound of his own name. “Yeah?”

Zoro kept his eyes trained straight ahead.

“Damn, how do you know all that?” Zoro marveled. 

“I just think that if I want to make seafood my livelihood and take from the sea’s bounty, I should learn as much about her as I can. Just seems like the respectful thing to do,” Sanji mused. 

Zoro hummed in understanding.

Zoro slipped an arm around Sanji’s waist to pinch him back, letting his hand linger on Sanji’s hip even after he got his revenge.

Leopard whipray.

Tarpon.

Smallmouth grunt.

“And… I think those are all the ones I know off the top of my head,” Sanji concluded.

Zebra shark.

Longcomb sawfish.

Humphead wrasse. 

Zoro snorted at that one and Sanji pinched him teasingly, halfheartedly scolding him to “quit being childish, that’s really what they’re called.”

Black tip reef shark.

Cownose ray.

French angelfish.

Slowly but surely, Zoro relaxed into his side, tilting his head onto Sanji’s shoulder. Sanji’s thumb stroked up and down his side absentmindedly.

Suddenly, the ‘rock’ Sanji had been pointing at moved, and ah, yes, /now/ Zoro could see the ridge leading down to a wide paddle of a tail fin. “Ohhh.”

“Goliath grouper,” Sanji told him with a chuckle. 

He kept his arm curled around Zoro as he continued to name the creatures.

Zoro leaned in, trying to line up his gaze with Sanji’s pointing. “All I see is rocks?”

“Okay then, it’s the rock with the spiky ridge going down the middle,” Sanji directed him.

Oh, see that big ol’ monster in the corner?”

Zoro wasn’t sure what he was supposed to be looking at. “Uh…?”

Sanji put an arm around Zoro’s waist, pressing their sides together. He pointed to where he was looking. “Right there, to the left.”

He hopped up and got closer to the glass, beckoning Zoro to follow him. “So, those big silver fish right there are giant trevally. The little black and white striped one is a banded butterflyfish. The ones with the bright blue fins are… blue tang surgeonfish?

“How many of these do you think you could name?” he asked as his eyes followed the path of a pair of bright yellow fish meandering around a pile of rocks.

“Hmm…” Sanji hummed thoughtfully. “Let’s see.”

They shyly stumbled their way through making plans to attend Franky and Robin’s wedding, trying not to think about the weight of it being their first event they would attend as a couple. During a lapse in the conversation, Zoro’s attention turned back to the tank.

As they dug in to the small feast laid out on the blanket, they talked about the new tasting menu that Sanji was working on and Zoro’s upcoming travel to an out-of-town tournament. They argued over theories about the campy sci-fi show Luffy had talked them into watching together.

“Oh…” Zoro breathed, dumbstruck. “I… yeah, okay…”

“Good.” Sanji squeezed his hand affectionately. “So, you gonna eat or what?”

He reached up to take Zoro’s hand and gently tugged him down so they were kneeling next to each other. “If this isn’t working, just tell me and I’ll do whatever it is that /does/ make you feel special. But… if this is okay, then will you let me? Because you deserve it.”

Sanji paused and sighed, a smile tugging at the corners of his mouth. He met Zoro’s gaze, holding it as he told him, “I’m doing /all this/ because it /is/ you. I already told you, marimo. I want to do nice things for you.”

Zoro watched him arranging little plates of this and that, carefully and beautifully, as if he had someone to impress. Zoro stood at the edge of the blanket, surveying the scene. 

“You know, you don’t have to do all this,” he said, gesturing at the display. “It’s just me.”

Sanji set the cooler down and tugged the duffel bag off of Zoro’s shoulder. He pulled a blanket from the duffel, spreading it out a few feet back from the glass. In short order he had produced an entire picnic dinner from the cooler, an impressive spread.

“Whale sharks,” Sanji said, following him. “Biggest species of shark in the world.”

“They’re fucking massive,” Zoro marveled quietly. He turned to look at Sanji over his shoulder. “Bet you could make one helluva fish fry with one of those.”

“They’re endangered, asshole.”

Most prominent, however, were three of the biggest fish Zoro had ever seen in his life: easily over twenty feet long, striped and spotted, languidly weaving their way through the space.

“Whoah…” He let go of Sanji’s hand to wander towards the tank. “What the hell are those?”
Schools of shiny silver fish swam between flocks of stingrays swooping and gliding through the water. Sharks prowled the depths of the enclosure while colorful fish darted between rocks.

Up ahead, the walls flowed with a splash of faint blue-green light. As they rounded the corner, the hallway opened up into a huge room. The entire far wall was glass.

[thread limit, brb]

Zoro was glad that Sanji was already turning away to lead them down the hall so he couldn’t see his face turning beet red.

Sanji led them down a meandering hall that started to slope downwards, curving to the right.

“What, you worried I’m gonna wander off?” Zoro asked, taking Sanji’s hand despite the reluctance of his tone. 

“Nah,” Sanji assured him, bringing their clasped hands up to his lips to graze Zoro’s knuckles, “I just wanna hold your hand.”

“We’ve got to walk down a little ways to get to where we’re going. There’s some emergency lights but it’s still pretty dark,” Sanji said as he pulled the door open. He turned towards Zoro and held out his hand.

Sanji waved his thanks at a security camera as they passed. They followed the narrow hallway down until they found a door marked “Corridor B”. Sanji pulled out his phone again and flipped on the flashlight.

As they exited the car, Sanji grabbed a duffel bag and a cooler from the back seat, handing the duffel to Zoro to carry. Just as his friend had promised, after a quick exchange of text messages they were buzzed in through the service door.

“And yes, indeed, it /is/ closed, but I know a guy who works security who owes me a favor. He’s going to buzz us in. We won’t exactly have free run of the place, but I did convince him to keep the lights on in one particular exhibit.”

“Isn’t it kind of late? There aren’t any cars around. Shouldn’t it be closed by now?” Zoro asked, thoroughly confused. 

“Ah! There it is!” Sanji pulled into a small lot next to what appeared to be a service door and put the car in park.

GRAND LINE CITY AQUARIUM

“The aquarium?” Zoro wondered out loud as they pulled around the back of the building. 

Sanji was driving slow, looking for something along the back wall of the building. “Very observant, my dear moss.”

He’d lived here most of his life and still had to use a GPS to get anywhere. At the very least, he could tell that they were headed towards the waterfront. 

Soon enough, they were pulling up to a large modern-looking blue building. As they turned a corner, a sign came into view:

“You’ve waited this long; I think you can wait ten more minutes,” Sanji said with a mischievous grin. Zoro rolled his eyes and looked out the passenger window, trying to discern where they might be headed. He wished this damn city was easier to navigate.

Sanji had asked to surprise him with something special for their third date. Zoro had been uneasy at first - he wasn’t a big fan of surprises - but he had eventually given in. 

“So,” Zoro spoke up as they drove, “can I know where we’re going yet?”

At the end of their second date, drinks at a bar downtown where classic arcade games lined the walls, Sanji had kissed him on the cheek as they parted. Zoro swore the spot where Sanji’s lips had brushed his skin felt warm for the whole rest of the night.
“In a good way!” he had insisted when he had said something about it to Sanji a week later. It was all just so /new/. Every touch was electric and full of meaning.

Their first date had been the classic dinner-and-a-movie at Sanji’s place. The first time Sanji had put his arm around Zoro, gently stroking the curve of his shoulder with his thumb as they watched the movie, Zoro had barely been able to breathe.

And of course, because he apparently liked to make his own life difficult, his first attempt was under the delicate circumstances of dating a longtime friend. Sanji had insisted that they take things slow at first, concerned about overwhelming Zoro with the shift.

Zoro felt heat rising in his cheeks as he stammered. “Just…just get in the car, will you?”

Sanji smirked and went to take his place in the driver’s seat. 

~*~*~

Zoro had never done anything like this before. Dating, that is.

“I can open the door for myself,” Zoro grumbled as he climbed in. Sanji just sighed, shutting the door behind him. He bent down, leaning through the open window. “I know you can open the damn door, moss. Just let me do nice things for you, okay?”

Zoro inhaled sharply, a thrill running through him. His hands hovered awkwardly by Sanji’s elbows, but before he could commit to the embrace Sanji was pulling away. He turned to open the car door, gesturing for Zoro to get in.

“Man, you sure know how to make a guy feel special,” Sanji teased. He pushed himself off the car and stepped right up into Zoro’s personal space. He slid his arms around Zoro’s waist and leaned in close to his ear. “Well, I’m not too proud to admit /I/ was eager to see /you/.”

Sanji had pulled up to the curb in front of Zoro’s house and was standing on the sidewalk, leaning casually against the passenger-side door. He grinned and gave Zoro a little wave. “That was fast. Eager to see me, marimo?”

Zoro rolled his eyes. “Tch, whatever.”

Over the years, Sanji had seen him at his most disheveled on several occasions and somehow he still liked Zoro enough to ask him out. Sanji wasn’t going to care!

He unzipped it again anyway. 

His cellphone chirped at him from his back pocket, alerting him to an incoming text.

Zoro adjusted his clothes in the mirror for the three hundredth time in the past five minutes. He had zipped and unzipped his jacket too many times to count, still unsure which way looked better. He couldn’t understand why he was so concerned - it was just Sanji, after all.
